            • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

              I said, further down, I was surprised many assumed this would be a big City win. Neither team has much beyond their first XI so a shootout was never on the cards. Tactically Ranieri got it spot-on starting with a 3-man midfield. This was always going to be a game the Mancs would dominate and make all the running in. Claudio was astute enough to realise this and prevent City from winning early on via the centre of the pitch. Leicester defended well for the most part and the downside of going 4-3-3/4-5-1 for Leicester was Vardy was isolated up front. In retrospect, Ulloa would've been a better horses-for-courses pick but how do you drop Vardy atm?! Nothing much happened in the last 10 minutes when fatigue set in for both teams. There should've been an extra rest day. It makes all the difference to muscle recovery and therefore performance. I thought both teams would at least score but the result was as expected. Leicester still doing very well indeed.

            • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

              @joc365- And zero strength in depth. An injury to Vardy or/and Mahrez would halve/quarter Leicester's attacking threat, an injury to Kante would make it much easier to penetrate Leicester's defence etc. The reason they clearly aren't title contenders is because they would need every planet to align in order for them to win. It's inconceivable that Vardy, Mahrez, Kante, Albrighton et al will stay injury-free or in the 1% chance they do, maintain their current level of performance for the rest of the season. Mahrez potentially can (remains to be seen) but he could very well be snapped up in January anyway since Leicester have neither the finances or pulling power to prevent a player joining a top EPL/SLL/GB team. I like what Ranieri has done and 5th is a genuine possibility but those dreaming of a top 4 spot much less the title are frankly deluding themselves in the same way the Southampton fans were last season. Would like to see a top 4 though at the expense of Spurs. :-p

            • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

              Not sure why so many are going for a comfortable Man City win. Man City have as much depth as Leicester despite spending millions and have hardly shown any form against the in-form teams. They have no genuine replacements for their first XI and that front 4 has no real penetration against a stoutly set up defence. It ends up being left to David Silva and as great as he is, he can't do it on his own. Ranieri likes 4-4-2 but after the game against Arsenal where they were essentially outgunned, I would like to see Inler come in as a midfield 3 with Drinkwater and Kante, drop Ulloa (although he would quite easily get the better of Otamendi), play Vardy in the 9 with Mahrez and Albrighton on the wings. Flamini did a very good job of shadowing Silva the other day, I suggest 1 of the Leicester midfielders do the same. The more congested midfield should make it more difficult for the City trio. Anyways, both teams will probably have to play their first XI so am going with a lethargic 1-1.
